Comment Content:
I'm a student as well and my setup is like toned down version of yours which will be best fit for *students in budget*, it goes like:

*Acer Aspire 7* (i5 9th gen, GTX1060, 512GB M.2, 8gb ram) |
*SSD 240GB* If you have an internal SSD from old setup you can use an external case & use it as external one which comes in handy!
*Logitech Mk240 Wireless keyboard & Mouse* It overall gives a clean look and is best for students in Budget as well!
*Cosmic Byte Asteroid Laptop Cooling Pad* It is a bit bigger and has 5 fans but is best for cooling and adjustments and best part is you dont need to keep high school notes anymore! (But it wont fit in minimal aesthetic look)
*A Chair?* So i got a similar one which have seriously improved my body posture & makes you feel productive. but i wish i had more adjustments than horizontal and some neck support ones
*Cosmic Byte C3070W Nebula gamepad* I've got this as a gift so the one i have is wired, they have other variant which is wireless and no doubt go for it!
*Skullcandy Hesh 3 wireless Headphones* (you can use them wired too) These are best ones provided by skullcandy so far, what makes them special is their battery (21 hours), 10min charge = 2 hour backup, The bass is not like any other skullcandy ones it's actually Perfect amount which makes these universal choice & i got them around 70 USD which is a steal! 

For other aesthetics i got a rgb lightings at the back of my table, on table i keep my laptop, keyboard mouse and a plant (alive one xD), skullcandy box (works as a headphone stand and looks dope), water bottle matching keyboard #StayHydrated, a rubik's cube and a thumbs up can used as pen stand/stationary organizer #ReUse and this all sums my setup.

Comment Content:
This is so bad for your ergonomics.
You probably often need custom keys on your laptop which are not present in external keyboards, so you have to reach those in that elevated and angled position you got up there. Uncomfy and totally not functional. There's too little space between the keyboard and the end of the desk, should be at least twice that. The screen is too elevated compared to your head, your eyes should always look down to a screen not have it in front of them. That cat lamp should be moved as it's in the way with the mouse and it's totally unecessary & non proper for studying or working although very cute.
In general, your old setup was WAY better.
Asset Title: My UNIVERSITY Desk Setup 2020

Comment Content:
aahh you do have a point there but I'll address your concerns one by one:
1. Yes there are custom keys on my laptop like volume up or down button, but the Anne 2 Pro has a software that allows remapping of keys and allows a great extent of customization of the keys and their functions. So after a bit of experimenting I do not need to use the keyboard on the laptop at all now 
2. It's more important to keep the elbow at a 90 degree angle as you reach for the keyboard so the space between the keyboard and the end of the desk does not really matter to me, also my chair has armrests which kind of acts like the extension of the table so I can rest my arm on it if I'm not typing or interacting with my keyboard.
3. The recommendation is to put the top of the screen at eye level (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F8_ME4VwTiw) you can watch this video by the Wall Street Journal for reference starting from 1:03, which talks about where the monitor should be with respect to the height and distance from the viewer. Yes, it's only a 15.6 inch screen but if I find the words too small, I just ZOOM IN to make reading notes more comfy. 
4. From the video you can see that I have plenty of space to move my mouse regardless if my cat lamp is there or not, also I tend to use a high DPI on my mouse so I do not need to move my hands that much when using the mouse. Finally to end my argument, the cat is too CUTE so I don't want to move it xD

Hope it answers your concerns, but thanks for watching the video and pointing those things out :)
